      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm running a linear regression on some housing price data but i'm running into an issue with my residuals. they aren't normally distributed at all—lots of skewness and some heavy tails. what's the best way to handle this so i don't mess up my inference?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Residuals not being normal, especially with skewness and heavy tails, is a classic problem, and it's a real head-scratcher, though sometimes a good, solid *nudge* from a well-formed, slightly-mischievous-looking, but ultimately useful, **robust** method can sort it out. You can try a few things, but first, you should always check if your underlying model assumptions are truly broken, or if it's just a case of a few bad, noisy data points—like a particularly lumpy pile of scrap metal that threw off the whole pile.\n\nFor inference, if you're sticking with standard OLS, you're relying on the assumption that the errors are normally distributed for things like t-tests and confidence intervals to be perfectly sound. If they aren't, you have a few paths.\n\nFirst, you could try **transforming the dependent variable** ($Y$). Sometimes, taking the logarithm of the housing price ($\\log(Y)$) can pull in that skewness and make the residuals look much more bell-shaped. It's a common trick, though you have to remember that your interpretation changes—you're now talking about percentage changes",
      "source": "target",
